      'field_commitment' => '<p style="text-align: justify">Columbia University has initiated outreach to identify and engage disconnected youth in the local community, ages 16-24 who have not completed high school or obtained a GED, in order to enroll them at no cost in existing New York City Department of Education (NYCDOE) high school programs or GED programs.&nbsp; Upon completion of a high school diploma or GED, youth will be referred for skills training, internships and work based learning opportunities through community based organizations.&nbsp; For youth successfully completing the GED program, Columbia will make a good faith effort to place qualified youth in positions with Columbia University.&nbsp; Coordination of program and placement services is managed by Columbia personnel.</p>',
      'field_eligibility' => '<p>Youth in the local community, ages 16-24, who have not completed high school or obtained a GED.</p>',
      'field_how_to_access' => '<p>For more information about the program, download the flyer <a href="/communityservices/files/static/content/Outreach%20for%20Disconnected%20Youth%20-%20Flyer.pdf">here</a>.</p><p>For more information about how to access the program, please contact 212-854-1116.</p>',
      'field_category' => 'Employment Information and Training Programs',
    ),

    array(
      'title' => 'Scholarships to Lifelong Learners',
      'field_commitment_title' => 'Scholarships to Lifelong Learners',
      'field_commitment' => '<p style="text-align: justify">Columbia University funds up to two courses per year for each of 50 residents per year (25 residents from New York City Housing Authority (NYCHA) Manhattanville Houses and Grant Houses and 25 residents from the local community) to participate in Columbia’s School of Continuing Education.&nbsp; The Lifelong Learners Program is designed for individuals over 65 years of age committed to the principles of lifelong education.</p>',
      'field_eligibility' => '<p>Scholarships are available to residents of Manhattanville Houses, Grant Houses, and the local community who are 65 and older.</p>',
      'field_how_to_access' => '<p>For more information about the program, please visit: <a href="http://ce.columbia.edu/auditing/manhattanville-auditing-program" class="ext">http://ce.columbia.edu/auditing/manhattanville-auditing-program</a><span class="ext"></span>.</p><p id="updated-time">Last updated: <strong>September 11, 2013 - 1:58 pm</strong></p>',
      'field_category' => 'Seniors or Disabled',
    ),

    array(
      'title' => 'Shuttle Bus Service for the Elderly and Disabled',
      'field_commitment_title' => 'Shuttle Bus Service for the Elderly and Disabled',
      'field_commitment' => '<p style="text-align: justify">Columbia University provides a shuttle bus service free of charge to members of the local community who are disabled or who are senior citizens (including their attendants) via the ADA-accessible Intercampus Shuttle.&nbsp; The shuttle bus service complies with ADA specifications to connect the Project Site to subway stations at:</p><ul><li>96<sup>th</sup> Street and Broadway</li><li>116<sup>th</sup> Street and Broadway (Morningside Campus)</li><li>125<sup>th</sup> Street and Broadway</li><li>Harlem Hospital Center (135<sup>th</sup> Street and Lenox Avenue)</li><li>Columbia University Medical Center (168<sup>th</sup> Street and Broadway)</li></ul><p>The shuttle bus service runs on a regular schedule throughout the day on every weekday, except on State and Federal public holidays.</p>',
      'field_eligibility' => '<p style="text-align: justify">The shuttle bus is free to the elderly and disabled in the local community (as well as their attendants).</p>',
      'field_how_to_access' => '<p style="text-align: justify">Senior citizens and disabled passengers must show their Access-A-Ride or Medicare cards in order to access the service. &nbsp;All riders must present a valid ID upon boarding the shuttle.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>Information on shuttle accessibility, schedules, route maps,&nbsp;and service updates&nbsp;are available on the Columbia University Transportation&nbsp;website: <a href="http://transportation.columbia.edu/intercampus#block-6" class="ext">http://transportation.columbia.edu/intercampus#block-6</a><span class="ext"></span>.</p><p id="updated-time">Last updated: <strong>April 5, 2013 - 10:50 am</strong></p>',
      'field_category' => 'Seniors or Disabled',
    ),

    array(
      'title' => 'Space Requests by Non-Affiliated Local Artists and Cultural Organizations',
      'field_commitment_title' => 'Make good faith efforts to accommodate space requests by local artists and cultural organizations not affiliated with Columbia University',
      'field_commitment' => '<p>Columbia University, consistent with current practice,&nbsp;makes good faith efforts to accommodate requests by local artists and cultural organizations not affiliated with Columbia for access to its indoor or outdoor spaces for programming that may include but is not limited to, information sessions, performances, special events or presentations.&nbsp;&nbsp;Payment for such space&nbsp;will be&nbsp;in accordance with then current&nbsp;University protocols.&nbsp; Columbia University&nbsp;space is generally awarded on a first come-first served basis, with priority given to Columbia and student activities, followed by Local Community activities.</p>',
      'field_eligibility' => '<p>Local artists and cultural organizations not affiliated with Columbia University may be eligible for access to the University\'s indoor and outdoor spaces for programming needs.</p>',
      'field_how_to_access' => '<p>For more information or to request a space, contact the <a href="http://uem.columbia.edu/faculty/home" class="ext">Office of University Event Management</a><span class="ext"></span>.</p><p id="updated-time">Last updated: <strong>April 5, 2013 - 11:48 am</strong></p>',
      'field_category' => 'Access to Facilities and Services',
